Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":4,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Johanna Burnell was born in 1378, in Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Hugh Burnell, was 31 and her mother, Philippa De La Pole, was 18. She married Roger Leigh about 1390, in Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1400, in Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1378–1400":"1378–1400","1371–1415":"1371–1415","1366–1420":"1366–1420","1398–1450":"1398–1450","1347–1420":"1347–1420","1360–1387":"1360–1387","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1371":"1371","1415":"1415","1347":"1347","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","1366":"1366","1387":"1387","1398":"1398","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England":"Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1378–1400":"1378–1400","1371–1415":"1371–1415","1366–1420":"1366–1420","1398–1450":"1398–1450","1347–1420":"1347–1420","1360–1387":"1360–1387","about 1390":"noin 1390","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1371":"1371","1415":"1415","1347":"1347","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","1366":"1366","1387":"1387","1398":"1398","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England":"Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1378–1400":"1378–1400","1371–1415":"1371–1415","1366–1420":"1366–1420","1398–1450":"1398–1450","1347–1420":"1347–1420","1360–1387":"1360–1387","about 1390":"environ 1390","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1371":"1371","1415":"1415","1347":"1347","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","1366":"1366","1387":"1387","1398":"1398","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","Acton Burnell, Shropshire, England":"Acton Burnell, Shropshire, Angleterre","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Johanna Burnell est née en 1378, à Acton Burnell, Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Hugh Burnell, avait 31 ans et sa mère, Philippa De La Pole, avait 18 ans. Elle a épousé Roger Leig